04357nam a22006015i 9780271089140DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710891407 a10.1515/97802710891402doi  a(DE-B1597)584371  a(OCoLC)1253314163  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aCayley, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIvan Illich :bAn Intellectual Journey /cDavid Cayley. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (560 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIvan Illich: 21st-Century Perspectives ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction Ivan Illich as I Knew Him -- tPrologue: Early Life -- t1. Exile -- t2. Cuernavaca -- t3. Church -- t4. Deschooling Society -- t5. Illich as Revolutionary -- t6. Disabling Professions -- t7. Certainties -- t8. Gender -- t9. Embodiment/Disembodiment -- t10. “A Bulldozer Lurks in Every Computer”: On Reading, Writing, and Language -- t11. To Hell with Life -- t12. Corruptio Optimi Pessima -- t13. Apocalypse -- t14. Illich’s Way of Life -- tEpilogue The Art of Suffering -- tConclusion: An Intellectual Journey -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the eighteen years since Ivan Illich’s death, David Cayley has been reflecting on the meaning of his friend and teacher’s life and work. Now, in Ivan Illich: An Intellectual Journey, he presents Illich’s body of thought, locating it in its own time and retrieving its relevance for ours.Ivan Illich (1926–2002) was a revolutionary figure in the Roman Catholic Church and in the wider field of cultural criticism that began to take shape in the 1960s. His advocacy of a new, de-clericalized church and his opposition to American missionary programs in Latin America, which he saw as reactionary and imperialist, brought him into conflict with the Vatican and led him to withdraw from direct service to the church in 1969. His institutional critiques of the 1970s, from Deschooling Society to Medical Nemesis, promoted what he called institutional or cultural revolution. The last twenty years of his life were occupied with developing his theory of modernity as an extension of church history. Ranging over every phase of Illich’s career and meditating on each of his books, Cayley finds Illich to be as relevant today as ever and more likely to be understood, now that the many convergent crises he foresaw are in full public view and the church that rejected him is paralyzed in its “folkloric” shell.Not a conventional biography, though attentive to how Illich lived, Cayley’s book is “continuing a conversation” with Illich that will engage anyone who is interested in theology, philosophy, history, and the Catholic Church.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074510840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027108914040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271089140423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271089140/original  a978-3-11-074510-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK